06868nam a22007695i 9780822397748DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19971997ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223977487 a10.1515/97808223977482doi  a(DE-B1597)554501  a(OCoLC)1158214491  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ1075b.R33 1997 7aSOC0180002bisacsh04a305.32/08922100aRace and the Subject of Masculinities /cMichael Uebel, Harilaos Stecopoulos. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (432 p.) :b23 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Americanists00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tMen in Color: Introducing Race and the Subject of Masculinities -- tI. READING MEN, READING RACE -- tDesire and Difference: Homosexuality, Race, Masculinity -- tFiedler and Sons -- tII. WHITE LIKE WHO? -- t"As Thoroughly Black as the Most Faithful Philanthropist Could Desire": Erotics of Race in Higginson's Army Life in a Black Regiment -- tMezz Mezzrow and the Voluntary Negro Blues -- tReading the Blackboard: Youth, Masculinity, and Racial Cross-Identification -- tThe World According to Normal Bean: Edgar Rice Burroughs's Popular Culture -- tAll the King's Men: Elvis Impersonators and White Working-Class Masculinity -- tIII. VISUALIZING RACE AND THE SUBJECT OF MASCULINITIES -- tThe Riddle of the Zoot: Malcolm Little and Black Cultural Politics during World War II -- t"The Cool Pose": Intersectionality, Masculinity, and Quiescence in the Comedy and Films of Richard Pryor and Eddie Murphy -- tThe White Man's Muscles -- tFists of Fury: Discourses of Race and Masculinity in the Martial Arts Cinema -- tPhotographies of Mourning: Melancholia and Ambivalence in Van Der Zee, Mapplethorpe, and Looking for Langston -- tIV. COMING AFTER -- tPecs and Reps: Muscling in on Race and the Subject of Masculinities -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough in recent years scholars have explored the cultural construction of masculinity, they have largely ignored the ways in which masculinity intersects with other categories of identity, particularly those of race and ethnicity. The essays in Race and the Subject of Masculinities address this concern and focus on the social construction of masculinity-black, white, ethnic, gay, and straight-in terms of the often complex and dynamic relationships among these inseparable categories.Discussing a wide range of subjects including the inherent homoeroticism of martial-arts cinema, the relationship between working-class ideologies and Elvis impersonators, the emergence of a gay, black masculine aesthetic in the works of James Van der Zee and Robert Mapplethorpe, and the comedy of Richard Pryor, Race and the Subject of Masculinities provides a variety of opportunities for thinking about how race, sexuality, and "manhood" are reinforced and reconstituted in today's society. Editors Harry Stecopoulos and Michael Uebel have gathered together essays that make clear how the formation of masculine identity is never as obvious as it might seem to be. Examining personas as varied as Eddie Murphy, Bruce Lee, Tarzan, Malcolm X, and Andre Gidé, these essays draw on feminist critique and queer theory to demonstrate how cross-identification through performance and spectatorship among men of different races and cultural backgrounds has served to redefine masculinity in contemporary culture. By taking seriously the role of race in the making of men, Race and the Subject of Masculinities offers an important challenge to the new studies of masculinity.Contributors. Herman Beavers, Jonathan Dollimore, Richard Dyer, Robin D. G. Kelly, Christopher Looby, Leerom Medovoi, Eric Lott, Deborah E. McDowell, José E. Muñoz, Harry Stecopoulos, Yvonne Tasker, Michael Uebel, Gayle Wal